  "prompt": "Why is John Wick called Baba Yaga?",
  "response": "John Wick is referred to as \"Baba Yaga\" in the \"John Wick\" film series as a nickname that signifies his fearsome reputation within the criminal underworld. The term \"Baba Yaga\" originates from Slavic folklore, where Baba Yaga is a supernatural being, often depicted as a witch or an old woman who lives in a hut that stands on chicken legs. She is known for being both a giver and taker of life, embodying a complex figure who can be either helpful or harmful.\n\nIn the context of the \"John Wick\" movies, the character Viggo Tarasov describes John Wick as \"the man you send to kill the boogeyman\" and likens him to Baba Yaga. This comparison emphasizes John Wick's deadly skills and his ability to navigate and dominate the dangerous world he inhabits. The nickname underscores his reputation as an almost mythical assassin, someone who is feared and respected by all who know of him.",
